{"batchcomplete":"","query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Trickle_charging","to":"Trickle charging"}],"pages":{"1705298":{"pageid":1705298,"ns":0,"title":"Trickle charging","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"'''Trickle charging''' means [[Battery charger|charging]] a fully charged [[battery (electricity)|battery]] under no-load at a rate equal to its [[self-discharge]] rate, thus enabling the battery to remain at its fully charged level.<ref name=\"CompanyDept1934\">{{cite book|author1=General Electric Company|author2=General Electric Company. Publicity Dept|title=General Electric review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uVFQAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=12 January 2012|year=1934|publisher=General Electric Co.}}</ref><ref name=\"Vinal1955\">{{cite book|author=George Wood Vinal|title=Storage batteries: a general treatise on the physics and chemistry of secondary batteries and their engineering applications|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zC1RAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=December 1955|publisher=Wiley}}</ref> A battery under continuous [[float voltage]] charging is said to be under '''float-charging'''.<ref name=\"Inc.1989\">{{cite book|author=InfoWorld Media Group, Inc.|title=InfoWorld|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=szAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT29|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=28 August 1989|publisher=InfoWorld Media Group, Inc.|page=29|issn=0199-6649}}</ref>\n\nFor lead-acid batteries under no-load float charging (such as in [[SLI battery|SLI batteries]]), trickle charging is achieved naturally at the end-of-charge, when the lead-acid battery takes in a trickle charge to keep itself fully charged. The trickle charging then equals the energy expended by the lead-acid battery in splitting the water in the electrolyte into hydrogen and oxygen gases.<ref name=\"Rand2004\">{{cite book|author=David Anthony James Rand|title=Valve-regulated lead-acid batteries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Rwryml3YMEC&pg=PA258|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=24 February 2004|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-444-50746-4|page=258}}</ref> Other technologies, such as the [[lithium-ion battery]] technology, are highly intolerant to over-charging, and cannot be float-charged without an external [[battery management system]].<ref name=\"Crompton2000\">{{cite book|author=Thomas Roy Crompton|title=Battery reference book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q58IX4BM7-0C&pg=SA47-PA14|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=11 May 2000|publisher=Newnes|isbn=978-0-7506-4625-3|page=47}}</ref><ref name=\"BergveldKruijt2002\">{{cite book|author1=Henk Jan Bergveld|author2=Wanda S. Kruijt|author3=Peter H. L. Notten|title=Battery management systems: design by modelling|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FVvo7W3Y7wgC&pg=PA171|accessdate=12 January 2012|date=1 November 2002|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-4020-0832-0|page=171}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Float voltage]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}} \n\n[[Category:Battery charging]]"}]}}}}